He is widely regarded as the father of theoretical computer science and artificial intelligence. Turing made significant contributions to the development of theoretical computer science by formalizing the concepts of algorithm and computation with the Turing machine. During World War II, he played a crucial role in cracking German codes at Bletchley Park, contributing to the Allied victory. Despite his remarkable achievements, Turing faced persecution for his homosexuality, and he tragically died by cyanide poisoning. Turing has since received posthumous apologies and recognition for his contributions.
